"dniw ekil swolf edoc"v
                      ≫

                      → , , , , , ↘
                    ↘
                    ≪→→t←           ↓

                    ,               ,

                    ,               ,

                    ,               ,

                    ,               ,

                    ,               ,

                    ↑               ↙

                      ↖ , , , , , ←

  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Output:  code flows like wind

  Notice there is no @ anywhere in this program. It still halts
  cleanly, exit 0. Two winds meet head-on at the eye of the spiral
  and the program ends.

  How it flows
  ------------
  Row 0 builds the message in reverse so 'c' lands on top of the
  stack, then `v` redirects the IP south. On the next tick, `≫`
  raises its speed to 2.

  From there the IP rides a clockwise rotation with diagonal
  corners — `↘ ↙ ↖` — at speed 2. The four edges of the rotation
  hold five `,` print cells each, evenly spaced at the speed-2
  stride:

    top edge        →  prints "code "
    right edge      →  prints "flows"
    bottom edge     →  prints " like"   (read west-to-east)
    left edge       →  prints " wind"

  After printing the final 'd' on the left edge at (20, 7), the
  IP advances north to (20, 5) — the eye of the storm. Three
  things happen there in quick succession:

    (20, 5)  ≪   speed drops to 1
    (20, 4)  ↘   redirect to south-east
    (21, 5)  →   set east

  Speed is now 1. The next two cells are `→` `→`, and then `t`:

    (22, 5)  →   continue east
    (23, 5)  t   SPLIT — spawn child at (22, 5) going west,
                  speed 1 (inherited from parent), empty stack.
                  Parent advances east to (24, 5).
    (24, 5)  ←   parent reverses, now heading west.

  On the next tick the parent and the child both arrive at
  (23, 5) — the same cell, from opposite sides:

    parent: (24, 5) ←  →  advances west to (23, 5)
    child:  (22, 5) →  →  advances east to (23, 5)

  End-of-tick collision pass (SPEC §3.8): two IPs share (23, 5).
  Direction sum is (-1, 0) + (+1, 0) = (0, 0) — head-on.
  The merged IP dies. Live IP list is now empty, so the runtime
  halts. No `@` ever runs.

  The drop to speed 1 is load-bearing
  ----------------------------------
  At speed 2 the parent only ever lands on even-x cells. The
  child of `t` is spawned at (parent_x − 1), which is odd-x
  while the parent traverses east-going edges, and never coincides
  with the parent again — they slide past each other on
  parities forever. Speed 1 puts both IPs back on a common
  parity, so the head-on merge can actually happen.

  In other words: the wind has to slow down for the storm to
  meet itself.

  All four v2.0 mechanics in one program
  --------------------------------------
  - Eight winds (the diagonal corner glyphs ↘ ↙ ↖ + cardinal → ↓ ↑ ←)
  - Wind speed (≫ on the way in, ≪ at the eye)
  - SPLIT (`t` creates the second IP)
  - IP collision merge (the program halts via head-on cancel,
    not via @)

  Things to notice
  ----------------
  - The corners of the rotation are visible 45° wedges in the
    source. The spiral isn't drawn over the source — the source
    *is* the spiral.

  - Step through it under `windy debug examples/anthem.wnd`. The
    state panel will show `ips: 1` for the entire outer rotation,
    flip to `ips: 2` on the tick `t` runs, and drop to `ips: 0`
    one tick later when the merge fires. That `2 → 0` transition
    is the halt.

  - The interior of the rotation isn't decorated this time —
    the action that fills it is the IP itself, on its way to
    the merge. Open the file in any text editor and the path
    is right there.
